<subSubSection id="1C99FA0C848FB19F64AB01D39281AEF3" pageId="3" pageNumber="142" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="A454A8DE6144B8C8C8C98D6EF08F134C" pageId="3" pageNumber="142">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="35ACEF81A021247FA8AA3C3D10683DFA" pageId="3" pageNumber="142">
<taxonomicName id="1B477AA12826340F703BFDFC3913B45C" authorityName="W. L. Wagner &amp; Lorence" authorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Oparanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="3" pageNumber="142" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tiva">
<emphasis id="C9E948F81DE124B3E5B73717756DBD82" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="142">Oparanthus tiva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has domatia (with an associated tuft of hairs) on the abaxial surface of the leaves. Domatia are essentially absent in the family, so domatia in 
<taxonomicName id="3D0D17D9B4CCB732ABD340600294B865" authorityName="W. L. Wagner &amp; Lorence" authorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Oparanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="3" pageNumber="142" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tiva">
<emphasis id="0B3ECFF8D0F4DF91F8D355FFBC792F64" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="142">Oparanthus tiva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be investigated further to understand the ecological significance. When domatia were discovered in 
<taxonomicName id="444D5168CDB79D5966B2FDB293944F72" authorityName="W. L. Wagner &amp; Lorence" authorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Oparanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="3" pageNumber="142" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tiva">
<emphasis id="8C15A58090ACF36E3C7A9DAFB9DFEC50" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="142">Oparanthus tiva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, we reexamined the other species of the genus and those of the closely related genus 
<taxonomicName id="65E6A2FF4F9A1B3C7A03F30AE2C4D5E1" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Fitchia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="142" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DDF9C577EAC5F3A42E5B8DA2D30242FB" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="142">Fitchia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. We found them only in the closest relative, 
<taxonomicName id="3757B4983B56A3CCD1490B1350F1FC8E" authorityName="R. K. Shannon &amp; W. L. Wagner" authorityYear="1997" baseAuthorityName="O. Deg. &amp; Sherff" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Oparanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="3" pageNumber="142" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hivoanus">
<emphasis id="244465F3B1EDA02E117076C9FAAE13E2" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="142">Oparanthus hivoanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and in the Nuku Hiva species, 
<taxonomicName id="33CA4870C042316BE9404A6430CE4D15" authorityName="W. L. Wagner &amp; Lorence" authorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Oparanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="3" pageNumber="142" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="woodii">
<emphasis id="DCD7F243583A4938D3DCEA73EEB15C80" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="142">Oparanthus woodii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but in these without the associated tuft of hairs covering the pit. 
<taxonomicName id="D612C906B6B69C840E3BCA77116C91F4" authorityName="W. L. Wagner &amp; Lorence" authorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Oparanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="3" pageNumber="142" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tiva">
<emphasis id="7DEA1E501D6D7522783AF2CE416C3832" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="142">Oparanthus tiva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a relatively rare species with an estimated 100 individuals known. It is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="6C9CA436FFB6FC701EE69025E06FBF79" authorityName="R. K. Shannon &amp; W. L. Wagner" authorityYear="1997" baseAuthorityName="O. Deg. &amp; Sherff" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Oparanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="3" pageNumber="142" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hivoanus">
<emphasis id="7A12CF4F89F64DF6A346A1F038732BD8" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="142">Oparanthus hivoanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the tree habit, leaves thinly coriaceous, 10-19.3 
<normalizedToken id="8E23733637B44558FABD248B249D225F" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6-15.8 cm, larger heads 9-14 mm in diameter, 10-20 mm high, receptacular bracts of ray florets 10-11 mm long, those of disk florets 12-13 mm long, and the sterile disk achenes 12-13.
</paragraph>
